# rust-overlay Guide for 2026

## 1) Adding rust-overlay as a Flake Input

To include rust-overlay in your Nix flake, add this to your `flake.nix`:

```nix
inputs = {
  nixpkgs.url = "github:NixOS/nixpkgs/nixos-unstable";
  rust-overlay.url = "github:oxalica/rust-overlay";
};
```

Then reference it in outputs: `{ nixpkgs, rust-overlay, ... }`

## 2) Best Practices for 2026

- **Always use `default` profile** unless you have specific needs. The documentation emphasizes: *"If not sure, always choose this"*
- **Avoid `rust-bin.nightly.latest`** — use `selectLatestNightlyWith` instead to prevent builds failing when components are unavailable
- **Stable versions are persistent** — versions 1.29.0 and newer are kept indefinitely
- **Nightly retention policy**: only versions from `{current_year - 1}-01-01` onward are maintained in the main branch

## 3) Using fromRustupToolchainFile

If you have an existing rustup `rust-toolchain` file, simplify your configuration:

```nix
rust-bin.fromRustupToolchainFile ./rust-toolchain
```

This automatically reads your rustup configuration file and applies those settings within Nix.

## 4) Recommended Flake Structure for Rust Development

```nix
{
  inputs = {
    nixpkgs.url = "github:NixOS/nixpkgs/nixos-unstable";
    rust-overlay.url = "github:oxalica/rust-overlay";
    flake-utils.url = "github:numtide/flake-utils";
  };

  outputs = { self, nixpkgs, rust-overlay, flake-utils, ... }:
    flake-utils.lib.eachDefaultSystem (system:
      let
        overlays = [ (import rust-overlay) ];
        pkgs = import nixpkgs { inherit system overlays; };
      in {
        devShells.default = with pkgs; mkShell {
          buildInputs = [ rust-bin.stable.latest.default ];
        };
      }
    );
}
```

## 5) Platform-Specific Considerations

The project targets *"x86\_64-linux with nixos-unstable and supported NixOS releases"* — these are officially tested. Other platforms may work but lack guaranteed support. For cross-compilation, consult the dedicated documentation in the repository.
